{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660058"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22671"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22671"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111365"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15618"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22671"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93495"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45323"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111365"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents with a six-month history of a painless swelling on the left side of his face. It has slowly increased in size with no skin change or facial weakness. He reports no weight loss, fever, trismus, dysphagia, dental pain, or recent infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has hypertension treated with perindopril. He does not smoke and drinks wine occasionally at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within reference limits. The swelling is clearly evident (\u003Ca href=\\\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6fDZlumXAEGudJtFHG5Osy7kcnU87i.jpg\\\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E). The lump is non-tender and facial movements are normal. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures has this lump most likely arisen from?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The skin","A cervical lymph node","The carotid artery","The mandible","The parotid gland"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESlowly enlarging, painless preauricular swellings with preserved facial nerve function are most commonly due to salivary gland pathology, particularly lesions of the parotid gland. Location anterior and inferior to the ear, mobility over underlying structures, intact overlying skin, and absence of facial nerve dysfunction all support a parotid origin. Initial evaluation typically includes targeted examination of facial nerve function and imaging, with fine needle aspiration cytology often used to guide further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe skin\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely because there is no overlying erythema, ulceration, punctum, or adherence of the mass to the dermis. The lesion appears to be deep to the skin in the preauricular region, which argues against a cutaneous cyst or skin adnexal tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA cervical lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the preauricular location overlying the parotid, the lack of infectious symptoms, and absence of other nodal enlargement. While intraparotid lymph nodes exist, a discrete, well-circumscribed mass within the parotid region with normal overlying skin and no systemic features points more strongly to a primary salivary lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E would present deeper in the upper neck at the carotid bifurcation, typically at the level of the hyoid, often as a pulsatile mass that may splay the carotid bifurcation on imaging. The preauricular location makes a carotid origin improbable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe mandible\u003C/strong\u003E would more likely cause bony tenderness, dental symptoms, trismus, or intraoral changes, which this patient does not have.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe parotid gland\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely source given the preauricular and angle-of-mandible location, slow painless growth, and intact facial nerve function. Common differentials include benign pleomorphic adenoma and Warthin tumour, though malignant salivary neoplasms and primary lymphoid lesions can occur; red flags would include rapid growth, pain, skin fixation, and facial weakness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A slow-growing, painless preauricular mass with intact facial nerve function most commonly suggests a parotid gland lesion.","Facial nerve weakness, skin fixation, pain or rapid growth increase concern for malignancy in salivary masses.","Initial work-up of a suspected parotid mass includes targeted examination for facial nerve function and imaging plus fine needle aspiration cytology."],"references":["Gandolphi MM, Slattery W. Parotid Gland Tumors and the Facial Nerve. Otolaryngol Clin N Am 2016; 49:425\u201334.","Kaminski B. Lymphomas of the head\u2011and\u2011neck region. J Cancer Res Ther. 2021; 17:1347-1350."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93495"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22671"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22031"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22031"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6fDZlumXAEGudJtFHG5Osy7kcnU87i.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6fDZlumXAEGudJtFHG5Osy7kcnU87i.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93495"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T13:01:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T13:02:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15618"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111365"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":